<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td valign=3D"top">
<h2><font color=3D"#D60021">1.3.5.9.</font></h2>
</td>
<td valign=3D"top">
<h2><i>F</i>-Test for Equality of Two Variances</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</td>
</tr>











<!-----begin section: purpose -->


<tr>
   <td width=3D"15%" valign=3D"top">
      <i>Purpose:<br>
         Test if variances from two populations are equal
      </i>
   </td>
   <td width=3D"85%" valign=3D"top">
      An <i>F</i>-test
      (<a href=3D"https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/eda/section4/eda=
43.htm#Snedecor">Snedecor and Cochran,
      1983</a>) is used to test if the variances of two
      populations are equal.  This test can be a two-tailed test or a
      one-tailed test.  The two-tailed version tests against the
      alternative that the variances are not equal.
      The one-tailed version only tests in one direction, that is
      the variance from the first population is either
      greater than or less than (but not both) the second population
      variance.  The choice is determined by the problem.
      For example, if we are testing a new process, we may only
      be interested in knowing if the new process is less variable
      than the old process.

   </td>
</tr>

<!-----begin section: definition -->

<tr>
   <td width=3D"15%" valign=3D"top">
      <i>Definition
      </i>
   </td>
   <td width=3D"85%" valign=3D"top">
      The <i>F</i> hypothesis test is defined as:
      <table>

      <tbody><tr>
         <td>
            H<sub>0</sub>:=20
         </td>
         <td>
            \( \sigma_{1}^{2} \) =3D \( \sigma_{2}^{2} \)
         </td>
       </tr>
      <tr>
         <td valign=3D"top">
            H<sub>a</sub>:
         </td>
         <td valign=3D"top">
            <table>
              <tbody><tr>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    \( \sigma_{1}^{2} &lt; \sigma_{2}^{2} \)
                 </td>
                 <td valign=3D"top">
                    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
                 </td>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    for a lower one-tailed test
                 </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    \( \sigma_{1}^{2} &gt; \sigma_{2}^{2} \)
                 </td>
                 <td valign=3D"top">
                    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
                 </td>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    for an upper one-tailed test
                 </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    \( \sigma_{1}^{2} \ne \sigma_{2}^{2} \)
                 </td>
                 <td valign=3D"top">
                    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
                 </td>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    for a two-tailed test
                 </td>
              </tr>
            </tbody></table>
         </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
         <td valign=3D"top">
            Test<br>
            Statistic:
         </td>
         <td>
            <b><i>F =3D</i></b>
            <!-- <img align=3Dtop src=3D"eqns/ftest.gif" alt=3D"s1**2/s2**2=
"> -->
            \( s^{2}_{1}/s^{2}_{2} \)
            <p>
            where
            <!-- <img align=3Dtop src=3D"eqns/s1sq.gif" alt=3D"s1**2"> -->
            \({s^{2}_{1}}\) and
            <!-- <img align=3Dtop src=3D"eqns/s2sq.gif" alt=3D"s2**2"> -->
            \({s^{2}_{2}}\) and are the sample variances.  The more this
            ratio deviates from 1, the stronger the evidence for unequal
            population variances.
         </p></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
         <td valign=3D"top">
            Significance<br>
            Level:
         </td>
         <td valign=3D"top">
            <!-- <img src=3D"eqns/alpha.gif" alt=3D"alpha"> -->
            <i>=CE=B1</i>
         </td>
       </tr>
      <tr>
         <td valign=3D"top">
            Critical<br>
            Region:
         </td>
         <td>
            The hypothesis that the two variances are equal
            is rejected if
            <p>
            <table>
              <tbody><tr>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    \( F &gt; F_{\alpha,N_1 - 1,N_2 - 1} \)
                 </td>
                 <td valign=3D"top">
                    &nbsp;&nbsp;
                 </td>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    for an upper one-tailed test
                 </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    \( F &lt; F_{1 - \alpha,N_1 - 1,N_2 - 1} \)
                 </td>
                 <td valign=3D"top">
                    &nbsp;&nbsp;
                 </td>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    for a lower one-tailed test
                 </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    \( F &lt; F_{1 - \alpha/2,N_1 - 1,N_2 - 1} \)
                    <p>
                    or
                    </p><p>
                    \( F &gt; F_{\alpha/2,N_1 - 1,N_2 - 1} \)
                 </p></td>
                 <td valign=3D"top">
                    &nbsp;&nbsp;
                 </td>
                 <td valign=3D"top" align=3D"left">
                    for a two-tailed test
                 </td>
              </tr>
            </tbody></table>
            where=20
            <big><i>F</i></big><sub><i>=CE=B1</i>, <i>N</i><sub>1</sub>-1,
            <i>N</i><sub>2</sub>-1</sub> is the
            <a href=3D"https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/eda/section=
3/eda3673.htm">critical value</a> of the
            <a href=3D"https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/eda/section=
3/eda3665.htm"><i>F</i> distribution</a> with
            <i>N</i><sub>1</sub>-1 and <i>N</i><sub>2</sub>-1
            degrees of freedom and a significance level of <i>=CE=B1</i>.
            </p><p>
            In the above formulas for the critical
            regions, the Handbook follows the convention that
            <big><i>F</i></big><sub><i>=CE=B1</i></sub>
            is the upper critical value from the <i>F</i> distribution
            and <big><i>F</i></big><sub>1-<i>=CE=B1</i></sub>
            is the lower critical value from the
            <i>F</i> distribution.  Note that this is the opposite of the
            designation used by some texts and software programs. =20
         </p></td>
      </tr>

     </tbody></table>
   </td>
</tr>

<!-----begin section: sample output -->


<tr>
   <td width=3D"15%" valign=3D"top">
      <i>F Test Example</i>
   </td>
   <td width=3D"85%" valign=3D"top">
The following <i>F</i>-test was generated for the=20
<!-- <a href=3D"eda3531.htm">AUTO83B.DAT</a> -->
<a href=3D"https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/datasets/JAHANMI2.DAT">=
JAHANMI2.DAT</a>
data set.  The data set contains 480 ceramic strength measurements
for two batches of material.  The summary statistics for each batch
are shown below.
<pre>BATCH 1:
   NUMBER OF OBSERVATIONS      =3D      240
   MEAN                        =3D    688.9987
   STANDARD DEVIATION          =3D    65.54909
 =20
BATCH 2:
   NUMBER OF OBSERVATIONS      =3D      240
   MEAN                        =3D    611.1559
   STANDARD DEVIATION          =3D    61.85425
</pre>
We are testing the null hypothesis that the variances for
the two batches are equal.=20
<pre>H<sub>0</sub>:  =CF=83<sub>1</sub><sup>2</sup> =3D =CF=83<sub>2</sub><=
sup>2</sup>=20
H<sub>a</sub>:  =CF=83<sub>1</sub><sup>2</sup> =E2=89=A0 =CF=83<sub>2</sub>=
<sup>2</sup>=20
<p>
Test statistic:  <i>F</i> =3D 1.123037
Numerator degrees of freedom:  <i>N</i><sub>1</sub> - 1 =3D 239
Denominator degrees of freedom:  <i>N</i><sub>2</sub> - 1 =3D 239
Significance level:  <i>=CE=B1</i> =3D 0.05
Critical values:  <i>F</i>(1-<i>=CE=B1</i>/2,<i>N</i><sub>1</sub>-1,<i>N</i=
><sub>2</sub>-1) =3D 0.7756
                  <i>F</i>(<i>=CE=B1</i>/2,<i>N</i><sub>1</sub>-1,<i>N</i><=
sub>2</sub>-1) =3D 1.2894
Rejection region:  Reject H<sub>0</sub> if <i>F</i> &lt; 0.7756 or <i>F</i>=
 &gt; 1.2894
</p></pre>
The <i>F</i> test indicates that there is not enough evidence to=20
reject the null hypothesis that the two batch variancess are equal at=20
the 0.05 significance level.=20
</td>
</tr>
<!-- end paragraph -->

<!-----begin section: questions -->
<tr>
   <td width=3D"15%" valign=3D"top">
      <i>Questions
      </i>
   </td>
   <td width=3D"85%" valign=3D"top">
      The <i>F</i>-test can be used to answer the following
      questions:
      <ol>
         <li>Do two samples come from populations with equal
             variancess?
         </li><li>Does a new process, treatment, or test
             reduce the variability of the current process?
      </li></ol>

   </td>
</tr>

